docs.abstract: The Trump team’s approach to the task of pigeonholing the challenger looked less focused than those used in 2004 and 2012.
docs.snippet: The Trump team’s approach to the task of pigeonholing the challenger looked less focused than those used in 2004 and 2012.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last two presidential re-election campaigns followed a similar playbook: define the opposition early on the most important issue, emphasize a few cultural wedge issues to rally the base while appealing to a few swing voters, and reinvigorate supporters at the convention. It was enough for George W. Bush in 2004 and Barack Obama in 2012 to flip their approval ratings from negative to positive, and to win re-election.

headline.main: Conventions Can Boost the Incumbent. Did It Work This Time?
headline.print_headline: Bush and Obama Saw  Post-Convention Bumps.  Can Trump Expect One?

docs.abstract: In the fight over the Dakota Access Pipeline, Native American activists achieved one of the most galvanizing environmental victories in years — and it all began with a group of teenagers.
docs.snippet: In the fight over the Dakota Access Pipeline, Native American activists achieved one of the most galvanizing environmental victories in years — and it all began with a group of teenagers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jasilyn Charger was 19 when she learned her best friend had killed herself. Charger was Lakota Sioux, and she had left the Cheyenne River Reservation in South Dakota for Portland, Ore., just a few months earlier. But in the summer of 2015, she flew home for her friend’s funeral. Then, two days later, while she was still in Eagle Butte — the largest town on the Cheyenne River Reservation with a population of 1,300 — another friend killed herself. Charger was shocked. “It hurt all of us because these were people who we thought we knew but really we had no idea what they were going through,” she said. “It really woke us up.”

headline.main: The Youth Group That Launched a Movement at Standing Rock

docs.lead_paragraph: COMPTON, Calif. — Brianna Noble was impossible to miss when she first appeared among the throngs of protesters in the crowded streets of Oakland, Calif., at the end of May. Riding her horse Dapper Dan, with a Black Lives Matter sign draped on the horse’s right side, she drew gasps from the demonstrators surrounding her.
